notesStmt.note: There are two physically distinct sections to the manuscript, copied by at least two different scribes, but both very similar in appearance, and certainly contemporary; the first section consists of fols. 1-56, with fol. 56 being a smaller folio tipped in at the end of the quire, blank on the verso, that provides the conclusion to the prayer on fol. 55v (it has glue marks on the verso, which are difficult to account for); and then a second section, fols. 57-end. It is possible that these two sections were even from independent, but contemporary manuscripts, but it seems most likely that the manuscript was copied in two sections (by two different scribes), perhaps working at the same time, and then joined together, explaining the necessity of completing the first section on an inserted folio, and erasing the first two lines at the beginning of the next section on the following folio
Huglo, M. Les manuscrits du Processional, Volume I, Autriche à Espagne, Répertoire international des sources musicales B XIV (1), Munich, 1999.

msContents.summary: This is a Northern French processional for the use of the Dominican nuns of Poissy from the second half of the fifteenth century. It contains various Latin processional texts with accompanying rubrics and chant notation.

msItem.title: Processional (Use of the Dominican nuns of Poissy)
Procession for the Purification of the Virgin
msItem.incipit: Omnipotens sempiterne deus qui hodierna die vnigenitum tuum . . .

msItem.title: Procession for Palm Sunday
msItem.incipit: Omnipotens sempiterne redemptor qui de celis ad terram . . .
msItem.explicit: . . . domini nomine amen

msItem.explicit: Sed tu domine

msItem.title: Gospel Reading after the Mandatum on Holy Thursday
msItem.incipit: In illo tempore. Ante diem festum pasche …
msItem.explicit: ut dilectio qua dilexisti me in ipsis sit et ego in ipsis

msItem.title: Adoration of the Cross on Holy Friday

msItem.incipit: Christus resurgens ex mortuis iam non moritur . . .
msItem.explicit: Dominum nostrum Ihesum Christum . . .

msItem.explicit: Qui tecum viuit et regnat per omnia saecula saeculorum amen

msItem.title: Procession for Corpus Christi

msItem.title: Procession for the Feast of Saint Dominic
msItem.explicit: Gloria patri et filio et spiritui sancto

msItem.title: Procession for the Reception of Legates
msItem.explicit: Domine si conversus fuerit populus tuus et oraverit ad sanctuarium tuum. Exaudi. Gloria in excelso

msItem.title: Procession for the Reception of a Secular Prince

msItem.explicit: . . . per christum dominum nostrum amen

msItem.title: Procession for the Feast of Corpus Christi
msItem.incipit: Panis oblatus celitus in altari proponitur

msItem.title: Procession for the Feast of Saint John the Baptist

msItem.explicit: cui nomen iohannes erat Qui uiam

msItem.explicit: predicator gratie nos junge beatis

msItem.title: Chants Accompanying the Profession of a Religious

msItem.explicit: inmensis monilibus ornauit me Quem cum

supportDesc.extent: iii+123+iii; 134 x 90 mm bound to 140 x 104 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Nineteenth-century foliation in ink, upper right recto

p.signatures: Remains of leaf and quire signatures with a letter designating the quire and roman numerals

layoutDesc.layout: Nineteen lines of text and four lines of square musical notation on four-line red staves, ruled lightly in red ink; written area: 95 x 67 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: Three three- to four-line red and blue initials, capitals touched in yellow, decorative initials within music, small initials in alternate red or blue, rubrics in red
[Flyleaf 1 verso]Note in ink: "processional a l'usage des dominicaines du couvent de St-Louis de Pissiaco"
[Flyleaf 1 verso]Note in pencil: "St. Louis de Poissy"

binding.p: Bound in late eighteenth-century morocco over pasteboards, gilt-tooled on spine with floral motifs in compartments, marbled endpapers, edges dyed red; title on spine: "PROCESSIONALE"

history.provenance: Written in the fifteenth century for use by a Dominican nun of the royal abbey of St.-Louis at Poissy; belonged to the abbé Jules Bonhomme, curé de Saint-Jean Baptiste de Grenelles, Paris, and chaplain to the Fort de l'Est, Paris, musicologist and author of numerous liturgical studies; his monogram and pencil notes in French on first endleaf, recording that a nineteenth-century pen inscription there, "processional a l'usage des dominicaines du couvert de St-Louis de Pissiaco" was that of the seller he purchased it from; pen inscription on last endleaf, "milieu du 15e," most probably in same hand, accompanied by other booksellers' marks, "no 1222 14" and "Li 24990."; purchased for Bryn Mawr College Library from the Howard Lehman Goodhart Memorial Fund
